	</div><div class="blogs_entrybody" style="clear:both">
		"They allow peer-to-peer clients on their network?  Scrap, where's the network guy?  What was his name?" I asked Scrap in a machine gun fashion."Well, boss, like I've been trying to say... nothing is really documented that well.  The network guy, errr, Kurt is working on a dying mail server and hasn't given me much time." Scrap responded.<br/><br/>I crumpled up some fancy artwork I was drawing on my notepad and tossed the museum piece into the garbage can.  "Alright, I'll go find Kurt.  Run back to the wiring closet and tap the inside interface of the firewall.  I want to know what machine or machines are serving up that P2P soup.  The minute you locate the machine(s), pull their plug(s)."<br/><br/>Scrap rubbed his hands together.  "Roger that." <br/><br/>I sprinted down the hall and almost ran John over.<br/><br/>"Woah!  Chief!  Something up?" John asked as he turned to walk with me.<br/><br/>"I need to talk to your network guy, Kurt.  He really hasn't been available much to answer our questions." I said, almost out of breath.<br/><br/>John didn't look happy.  "What?  I told everyone, especially Kurt, that they needed to be available.  Let me take care of..." <br/><br/>"John, seriously... it's okay.  I'll find him.  Thanks anyway." I said as I opened the door to Treesoft's server room.<br/><br/>John's behavior was very bipolar.  One moment he was the happy company man, the next moment he was the only guy not wearing deodorant at a cocktail party full of fashion models.  Strange.<br/><br/>I found Kurt curled up next to a large midrange server on the floor.  He appeared to be locking the server's external case and about to power the machine back up.<br/><br/>"Hey Kurt, all done?" I asked.<br/><br/>Kurt stood up and towered over me by at least a foot.  The man was huge.<br/><br/>"Yeah, I think so.  Looks like my RAID controller went south, but I'm hoping that my array is still intact.  I guess I'll find out after I hit the power button." Kurt said as he powered up the machine.  <br/><br/>"Kurt, real quick... Scrap found some P2P traffic between the internal Treesoft network and the internet.  Do you allow P2P clients on the internal network?" I asked.  <br/><br/>My neck was becoming stiff from looking up at Kurt, so I took a few steps back.<br/><br/>"P2P?  Hell no.  We went through this about a year ago.  You found some P2P traffic?  What machine is it coming from?" Kurt asked as he watched the server scroll POST messages on the server's console screen.<br/><br/>"Scrap is finding that out now.  Do you have a moment?  We could really use your knowledge of the network." I begged.<br/><br/>"YES!  YES!" Kurt screamed as he slammed his huge hands together.<br/><br/>"Wow, I'm glad you're excited about helping." I laughed.<br/><br/>"Nah, my array is fine.  Phew.  There was a lot of mail on there.  Okay, let's go find your friend." Kurt said with a grin.  <br/><br/>We wandered down another hall and found Scrap sitting on the floor of the wiring closet, staring at his Scraptop screen.<br/><br/>"Yo." I said as I walked in behind Kurt.  "What do you have?" <br/><br/>Scrap looked up from the Scraptop.<br/><br/>"One internal IP address." Scrap replied.  "10.0.1.75, and I was about to see who owns that puppy!"<br/><br/><b>scraptop:~ scrap$ nmblookup -A 10.0.1.75<br/>Looking up status of 10.0.1.75<br/>        DELL1234      &lt;00&gt; -         P <active> <br/>        TREESOFT            &lt;00&gt; - <group> P <active> <br/>        DELL1234      &lt;03&gt; -         P <active> <br/>        DELL1234$     &lt;03&gt; -         P <active> <br/>        SSVENSON        &lt;03&gt; -         P <active> <br/>        MAC Address = XX-XX-XX-XX-XX-XX<br/>scraptop:~ scrap$ </b><br/><br/>Kurt did not look amused.<br/><br/><p><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20100707130404/http://www.esbn.org/esbn/verify.asp?id=91355-060223-830681-62"><img alt="esbn" src="https://web.archive.org/web/20100707130404im_/http://esbn.org/esbn/esbnicon.asp?id=9135506022383068162" border="0"> ESBN 91355-060223-830681-62</a><br><img src="https://web.archive.org/web/20100707130404im_/http://esbn.org/esbn/barcode.asp?code=9135506022383068162&amp;height=20&amp;width=1&amp;mode=code39"></p><p><hr><table width="100%" bgcolor="#FFFFCC" cellpadding="9px">
<tr><td><img style="margin-right: 9px; float: left" src="https://web.archive.org/web/20100707130404im_/http://userimages.ittoolbox.com/user/s_610000.jpg"><b><font face="Arial" size="4">DID YOU KNOW?</b></font><font face="Arial" size="2"><p style="margin-top: 2px">You can read all of SecurityMonkey's case files! <br>Find them <b><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20100707130404/http://blogs.ittoolbox.com/security/investigator/archives/official-securitymonkey-case-file-index-14787">here</a></b>. <br><br>You can also read all of SecurityMonkey's <br>'Banana Cupboard' stories <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20100707130404/http://blogs.ittoolbox.com/security/investigator/archives/banana-cupboard-stories-index-25647">here</a>.  <br><br>You may not get a lot done for a few hours... or even days.</font><br><br>The reviews are in...<br><br><i>"Completely addictive... suspenseful and informative at the same time!"<br>"A mix of classic detective scripting, timing, and technology..."<br>"Cleverly injected humor makes these case files easy to read and hard to put down!"</i></td></tr></table><hr><p>
